*label: bookmark

*label: debate_instructions_intro
*header: How the task works

In this task, you’ll judge a debate between *Debater A* and *Debater B* about a challenging question.

The debate happens over *4 turns*. For each turn, you will:
1) Click a link that opens that turn in a new tab  
2) Read the Key Question, the debaters’ positions, and any additional info provided
3) Give a probability judgment and answer a free-response question
4) Copy the *encoded version* of your answers and paste it back into this study (we'll explain what this means in a moment)

You do *not* need to be an expert in the specific topic of the question. We mainly care about how you reason with what you’re given.

*button: Next

*header: Giving your judgment

Each debate page will ask you to assign a probability that *Debater A* vs *Debater B* matches what an expert would say.

- If you have *no idea* who is right, set the slider to 50%/50%.
- If you lean one way, move the slider to reflect that (e.g., 40%/60%, 70%/30%, etc.).
- If the question seems a bit ambiguous, do your best to answer the way you think the expert who wrote the question would interpret it.

You’ll also be asked to explain *why* you chose the probability that you chose. We'd like you to list all relevant reasons that come to mind, with a brief remark on how much weight you gave to each.

*button: Next

*header: Timing

You will have a maximum time limit for each debate turn:
- *Turn 1:* 9 minutes  
- *Turn 2:* 9 minutes  
- *Turn 3:* 9 minutes  
- *Turn 4:* 9 minutes  

You don’t need to use all the time, but you should take as much time as you need (within the limit) to be as accurate as you can, and to provide a complete answer to the question provided.

When time runs out, the text box will disappear and you will no longer be able to edit your answer. However, you will still be able to copy your answer from the debate page. If you’re worried about time, it can help to type a short draft answer early, then improve it if you have time left.

*button: Next

*header: What you may and may not consult

To keep the task fair and consistent:

- *Do not* use the internet (Google, Wikipedia, forums, etc.) to help you evaluate the debate.
- *Do not* use any large language model or AI assistant.

*label: debate_instructions_video

*header: Watch the demo video

Before you start Turn 1, please watch the demo video explaining the interface. 

You do not need to re-watch the video if you have already seen it in a study earlier in this series.

[Watch the demo video (not required if you have already seen it in a study earlier in this series)|https://drive.google.com/file/d/1YE0nxKBQto0xHIjkHNjxiP2ocwnJcKIZ/view?usp=sharing]

*question: I watched the demo video, OR I have seen the video already
	*save: watched_demo_video
	Yes - continue to the debate
	
*New information: What to do if the task feels overwhelming*

*image: https://images.guidedtrack.com/new_information_rj9h0g4.jpg

Depending on the debate you receive, it is possible that you may be given an amount of information that feels simply impossible to read or comprehend in the amount of time given. In such cases, we recommend you do your best to orient yourself to the question and any relevant definitions, scroll down to the debate, and do your best with the information available to you in the time you have.

In case it is useful, in most browsers, you can press Ctrl+F (or Command+F) to search the current webpage for a particular word or phrase.

*button: OK

*New information: references*

*image: https://images.guidedtrack.com/new_information_rj9h0g4.jpg

Debaters may cite sources that appear as 'Year, title, and link blinded from debate judges.' This is intentional, not a glitch. These are genuine academic papers, and any figures or facts attributed to them do come from those sources.

Similarly, some sources may include a quote, along with the phrase *"URL blinded from debate judges"*. You can be assured that such quotes have indeed been pulled from reputable online sources.

